the basic decisions I remember, General

27:41.129 --> 27:49.461
Holloway, at that time Colonel Holloway, he and I 
were sitting in a little office about eight by

27:50.133 --> 27:55.740
eight feet, and trying to figure out, well, how are 
we going to get the Canadians to participate in

27:50.133 --> 27:55.740
this? They can't afford it. And I said, why don't we 
think in terms of, we'll pay two-thirds, you pay

27:57.542 --> 28:01.326
one-third. That stuck from then on, and that was 
the basis for the original planning of all the pine

28:03.008 --> 28:17.085
tree air defenses, which were the first radar I put 
along the southern Canadian border adjacent to

28:03.008 --> 28:17.085
the United States and up the Labrador coast. And 
then the due line, which eventually was put across

28:17.487 --> 28:25.842
northern Canada, they paid for one-third and they 
