what they had and what we had, where we saw and so

28:51.274 --> 29:04.430
forth, I think it was commendable that they agreed 
to pay for one third of it. Sure. But they had a lot of

29:04.571 --> 29:08.115
other stipulations that was to their favor much 
more than just dollar bills. For instance, to

29:13.420 --> 29:23.049
build radar sites, we had to use Canadian labor and 
Canadian organizations, so that gave them

29:13.420 --> 29:23.049
stimulated economy and industry.

29:25.632 --> 29:27.814
They permitted us to man certain stations. They 
didn't have the manpower to do it. Some production

29:31.097 --> 29:35.942
of radars and the gear, that kind of gear, went to 
radar sites. had to be produced in Canada. So

29:39.528 --> 29:49.121
really saying it, you know, we'd pay one-third, 
we'd pay two-thirds, really they got a lot more out

29:39.528 --> 29:49.121
of it than we did, but it was worth it. And that basic 
type planning grew eventually what turned out to

29:49.461 --> 29:55.088
be NORAD. And, of course, the deputy commander was 
a marshal, a four-star general from the Royal

29:55.168 --> 30:05.642
Canadian Air Force. Are the British included in 
this? No, no. It's RCAM, Royal Canadian Air Force.

30:16.548 --> 30:22.775
