This was back right after the war was over. They 
began to establish and think in terms of training

41:36.600 --> 41:49.874
and education then, and orienting themselves to 
terrific demobilization and just getting rid of

41:36.600 --> 41:49.874
all the experience they have. And they could 
foresee bringing in new people and training and

41:49.914 --> 41:54.298
educating them. And they saw the benefits and 
advantages educated people, in particular in the

41:56.971 --> 42:07.926
latest tactics and strategy that we had learned, 
you know, in this tremendous worldwide war, World

41:56.971 --> 42:07.926
War II. And they wanted to be able to teach this to 
the new incoming young people. And so it was

42:16.577 --> 42:24.868
shortly after the war, in the early, mid and late 
40s, that they began to plan for this. It was also a

42:25.169 --> 42:54.889
feather in the cap of a young, ambitious officer to 
be chosen to go to these schools, because if you

42:25.169 --> 42:54.889
were chosen to go to the school and you had this on 
your record, then you felt that you were in towards

42:25.169 --> 42:54.889
promotion and being, you know, like you go from 
squadron officer school to the staff course, then

42:25.169 --> 42:54.889
to the, eventually to the Air War College, and then 
even eventually, well, that to the National War

42:25.169 --> 42:54.889
College, which was a joint school in Washington, 
D.C. So I was delighted, and as a matter of fact, I

42:56.388 --> 43:01.256
wanted to go. I remember doing some soul 
searching, and I think all of us did that. Is this

43:07.064 --> 43:20.225
really the best route to take to spend a year in a 
school and miss some command opportunities for,

43:07.064 --> 43:20.225
let's say, some newly formed jet organizations, 
fighter organizations? You ask yourself that

43:20.706 --> 43:22.969
question a lot of times, I finally decided, and 
talked to a lot of my senior officers, the

43:23.506 --> 43:33.016
commander, that it was best to go to the Air Force. 
